The Kingdom of Poland ([Polish](/Polish_language): Królestwo Polskie ; [Latin](/Latin): Regnum Poloniae ) was a [monarchy](/Monarchy) in [Central Europe](/Central_Europe) that existed intermittently from the coronation of the first king, [Bolesław I the Brave](/Boles%C5%82aw_I_the_Brave), in 1025, to the collapse of the state as a result of the partitions and the abdication of the last monarch, [Stanisław August Poniatowski](/Stanis%C5%82aw_August_Poniatowski), in 1795. 

Until 1320, only a few of the most powerful princes of the Piast dynasty managed to have themselves crowned as kings, due to the division of the realm among members of the ruling dynasty and the absence of a single strong center of power. For a brief period between 1300 and 1306, the Kingdom of Poland was ruled by the Bohemian kings, creating a situation of personal union between the two states. In 1320, following the coronation of Władysław the Elbow-high, subsequent Polish rulers were crowned as kings.

In the second half of the 14th century, the concept of the [Crown of the Kingdom of Poland](/Crown_of_the_Kingdom_of_Poland) emerged. It emphasized the role of the [Crown](/Crown_of_Boles%C5%82aw_I_the_Brave) as the true, indivisible, and permanent sovereign of the Kingdom, distinct from the person of the reigning monarch, as well as emphasizing the unity of the Polish lands lying outside the borders of the kingdom. Alongside the King, the Crown’s authority was also shared by the developing parliament, known as the [Sejm](/Sejm_of_the_Polish%E2%80%93Lithuanian_Commonwealth), which included representatives of the kingdom’s nobility. This growing influence was expressed through participation in the election of rulers. Initially, from the early 15th century onward, only the most powerful magnates sitting in the [Senate](/Senate_of_Poland) took part, confirming the succession within the ruling [Jagiellonian dynasty](/Jagiellonian_dynasty). After the childless death of [Sigismund Augustus](/Sigismund_II_Augustus) in 1572, the procedure of the “[free election](/Royal_elections_in_Poland)” took shape, in which every nobleman had the right to participate and the list of candidates was no longer limited to a single ruling family. The last free election took place in 1764, at which Stanisław August was elected.

From the late 14th century, the Kingdom of Poland entered into close relations with the [Grand Duchy of Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania), appointing as co-ruler, through his marriage to [Queen Jadwiga](/Queen_Jadwiga), the grand duke [Władysław Jagiełło](/W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw_Jagie%C5%82%C5%82o). In 1413, the [Union of Horodło](/Union_of_Horod%C5%82o) was concluded, in which, alongside the monarchs, the lords of both polities also took part. The [personal union](/Personal_union), interrupted only occasionally, was transformed into a real union and the creation of a joint state, the [Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth](/Polish%E2%80%93Lithuanian_Commonwealth), referred to by contemporaries mostly as the Kingdom of Poland and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania. Over time, a custom emerged of referring to the Polish part of the joint state as “the Crown” and the Lithuanian part as “the Grand Duchy.” During this period, the Commonwealth, and with it the Kingdom of Poland, entered into personal unions with the [Kingdom of Sweden](/Kingdom_of_Sweden) (1592–1599) and the [Electorate of Saxony](/Electorate_of_Saxony) (1697–1763).

Under the partition agreements between [Prussia](/Prussia), the [Habsburgs](/Habsburg_monarchy), and [Russia](/Russia), the Kingdom of Poland ceased to exist. According to the 1797 convention, it was decided that the Kingdom of Poland was “from now on and forever abolished,” and none of the three courts would seek its restoration. During the [Napoleonic period](/Napoleonic_period), efforts to rebuild the Kingdom, supported by France, emerged, but in practice only the Duchy of Warsaw was created. At the [Congress of Vienna](/Congress_of_Vienna), the [Kingdom of Poland](/Congress_Poland) was established, tied to Russia through the person of its ruler and largely dependent on it. After subsequent uprisings, its autonomy was gradually reduced, but it formally existed until 1915. After the occupation of central Polish lands by German and Austrian forces, the creation of a German-dependent [Kingdom of Poland](/Kingdom_of_Poland_(1917%E2%80%931918)), administered by the [Regency Council](/Regency_Council_(Poland)), was proclaimed. After Poland regained independence, the Council transferred authority to a democratically elected government, and no further real attempts were made to restore monarchy in Poland.

