Establishment
-------------

The [West Slavic](/West_Slavs) tribe of [Polans](/Polans_(western)) who lived in what is today the historic region of [Greater Poland](/Greater_Poland), gave rise to a state in the early 10th century, which would become the nascent predecessor of the Kingdom of Poland. Following the [Christianization of Poland](/Christianization_of_Poland) in 966, and the emergence of the [Duchy of Poland](/Duchy_of_Poland) during the rule of [Mieszko I](/Mieszko_I), his eldest son [Bolesław I the Brave](/Boles%C5%82aw_I_the_Brave) inherited his father's dukedom and subsequently was crowned as king. [Crown of Bolesław I the Brave](/Crown_of_Boles%C5%82aw_I_the_Brave), along with royal [regalia](/Regalia)

In 1025, [Bolesław I the Brave](/Boles%C5%82aw_I_the_Brave) of the [Piast dynasty](/Piast_dynasty) was crowned the first [King of Poland](/List_of_Polish_monarchs) at [Gniezno Cathedral](/Gniezno_Cathedral), elevating Poland from a [duchy](/Duchy) to a [kingdom](/Monarchy) with the approval of [Pope John XIX](/Pope_John_XIX). Following the death of Bolesław, his son [Mieszko II Lambert](/Mieszko_II_Lambert) inherited the crown and a vast territory after his father, which included [Greater Poland](/Greater_Poland) (with [Mazovia](/Mazovia)), [Lesser Poland](/Lesser_Poland), [Silesia](/Silesia), [Pomerania](/Pomerania), [Lusatia](/Lusatia), [Moravia](/Moravia), [Red Ruthenia](/Red_Ruthenia), and [Upper Hungary](/Upper_Hungary). However, in 1031, he was forced to renounce the title and flee the country when a series of peasant uprisings broke out in what became known as the [pagan reaction](/Pagan_reaction_in_Poland), and [Yaroslav I the Wise](/Yaroslav_I_the_Wise), the [Grand Prince of Kiev](/Grand_Prince_of_Kiev), invaded the country from the east while Mieszko II was in Lusatia fighting the Holy Roman Emperor, [Conrad II](/Conrad_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor). Yaroslav I installed his ally, the half-brother of Mieszko II, Duke [Bezprym](/Bezprym), as the ruler of Poland. However, as a result of the upheavals, the kingdom suffered territorial losses and was effectively reduced to a duchy.

[Casimir I the Restorer](/Casimir_I_the_Restorer) managed to reunite parts of the kingdom following the crisis and moved the capital to [Kraków](/Krak%C3%B3w). However, he failed to reinstitute the monarchy due to opposition from the [Holy Roman Emperor](/Holy_Roman_Emperor). In 1076, [Bolesław II the Bold](/Boles%C5%82aw_II_the_Bold), with the support of [Pope Gregory VII](/Pope_Gregory_VII), regained the royal crown but was later [excommunicated](/Excommunication) and banished from the kingdom in 1079 for murdering his opponent, Bishop [Stanislaus of Szczepanów](/Stanislaus_of_Szczepan%C3%B3w). In 1079, [Władysław I Herman](/W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw_I_Herman), who never pursued kingship took over the reins after the expulsion of Bolesław II. Władysław I was disinterested in becoming king and the country was effectively run by [wojewoda](/Voivode) [Sieciech](/Sieciech).

Feudal fragmentation
--------------------

The [fragmentation](/Feudal_fragmentation) of Poland in 1138

In 1102, [Bolesław III Wrymouth](/Boles%C5%82aw_III_Wrymouth) became the ruler of Poland. Unlike Władysław I, Bolesław III proved to be a capable leader who restored the full territorial integrity of Poland but ultimately was not able to obtain the royal crown due to continued opposition from the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire). Upon his death in 1138, [the country was divided between his sons](/Testament_of_Boles%C5%82aw_III_Wrymouth) into the duchies of [Greater Poland](/Greater_Poland), [Lesser Poland](/Lesser_Poland), [Masovia](/Masovia), [Silesia](/Silesia), [Sandomierz](/Sandomierz), and a [Pomeranian](/Pomerania) [vassal](/Vassal_state). As a result, Poland entered a period of [feudal fragmentation](/Feudal_fragmentation) that lasted for over 200 years.

During the first half of the 13th century, the [Silesian Piasts](/Silesian_Piasts) attempted to restore the kingdom. [Henry the Bearded](/Henry_the_Bearded) undertook efforts to reunite the fragmented duchies through a combination of political maneuvering and conquest. He also undertook efforts towards the coronation of his son, [Henry II the Pious](/Henry_II_the_Pious), and negotiated with other Polish dukes and the Holy Roman Emperor, [Frederick II of Hohenstaufen](/Frederick_II_of_Hohenstaufen), to this end. Henry II, continued his father's efforts, but the [first Mongol invasion](/First_Mongol_invasion_of_Poland) in 1241 and his death at the [Battle of Legnica](/Battle_of_Legnica), abruptly halted the unification process.

Reunified kingdom
-----------------

Depiction of a royal assembly ( [Wiec](/Veche) ) in the reign of [Casimir III](/Casimir_III_of_Poland), 1333-1370
[Wawel Castle](/Wawel_Castle) in [Kraków](/Krak%C3%B3w) was the residence of the Polish kings from 1038 until 1598.

The next attempt to restore the monarchy and unify the Polish kingdom would occur in 1296, when [Przemysł II](/Przemys%C5%82_II) was crowned as the King of Poland in Gniezno. The coronation did not require papal consent as the title of king was already instituted in 1025. However, his reign was short-lived, as he was murdered by assassins sent by the margraviates of [Brandenburg](/Margraviate_of_Brandenburg). After the killing of [Przemysł II](/Przemys%C5%82_II), next to take the title of king was [Wenceslaus II of Bohemia](/Wenceslaus_II_of_Bohemia) from the Czech [Přemyslid dynasty](/P%C5%99emyslid_dynasty), who reigned until 1305. Following a vacancy that lasted until 1320, the Kingdom of Poland was fully restored under [Władysław I the Elbow-High](/W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw_I_the_Elbow-High), who was crowned at the [Wawel](/Wawel) [cathedral](/Wawel_Cathedral) in [Kraków](/Krak%C3%B3w), and then subsequently strengthened by his son [Casimir III the Great](/Casimir_III_the_Great), who expanded into Red Ruthenia. However, he had to renounce his claims to Silesia in order to secure peace with the Holy Roman Empire. Casimir III is the only Polish king to receive the title "Great", and his reign was marked by substantial developments in the kingdom's urban infrastructure, civic administration, and military strength. After his death on 5 November 1370, the rule of the Piast dynasty would come to an end.

Following the death of Casimir III, who died without an heir, [Louis I of Hungary](/Louis_I_of_Hungary) from the [House of Anjou](/Capetian_House_of_Anjou) became king in 1370. The period of his transitional rule also marked the rise of the nobility in the political life of the country. When Louis I died in 1382, his daughter [Jadwiga](/Jadwiga_of_Poland) took over the throne as King of Poland. Her advisors negotiated with [Jogaila](/W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw_II_Jagie%C5%82%C5%82o) of [Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania), concerning a potential marriage to Jadwiga. Jogaila pledged to convert to [Christianity](/Christianity) and signed the [Union of Krewo](/Union_of_Krewo) in 1385. The agreement also heralded a change in the legal status of the Polish realm to that of a [Crown of the Kingdom of Poland](/Crown_of_the_Kingdom_of_Poland), which was a political concept that assumed unbroken unity, indivisibility and continuity of the state. According to this concept, the Kingdom of Poland ceased to be the [patrimonial](/Patrimonialism) property of a [monarch](/Monarch) or [dynasty](/Dynasty), and became a common good of the political community of the Polish kingdom. After the conclusion of the union, Queen Jadwiga married Grand Duke Jogaila, who was crowned as King Władysław II Jagiełło on 4 March 1386, an event that marked the beginning of the [Jagiellon dynasty](/Jagiellon_dynasty).

